July 24 :  Data collection (Nene, Bibi)At the beginning of week three, our aim is to gather the data to complete at least 90% data collection andÂ we will be focusing on collecting data from signal shift cohort.
This one hour game will be divided into six sections in which is around ten minutes play.
And during each section testers have to answer two questions to measure how they feel in the game?
(A) How would you rate your level of mental fatigue?

(B) Is it difficult to concentrate?1)The game is mainly a repetitive exercise where you will be asked to identify the original set of five-red coloured balls among ten balls which appeared at the start of each session.
2) You will be asked to wear two kinds of physiological measuring device to measure your: Â  Â  Â  a) Heart rate variability andÂ Â  Â  Â  b) Changes in your brain waves as you play the game.
These devices will be washed and cleaned when it is handed on to you.
3) The game will take approximately half an hour to set up and 1 hour to play, but please spare at least 2 hours of your time for this activity.
4) One of the team members will provide testers the background information before starting the game and will be there to help testers during the game in case something goes wrong.
Making sure devices are well-connected.(Appeared green colour).

It was excited finally to receive the data from Fifi.
There are four files - EEG data, PR data, Performance data, Questionnaire data.
As for me, it is not easy work to get started quickly.
Take EEG data for example, to read these columns took me time to understand what the terminology stands for.
But it is interesting when you learn from these data which is like solving the puzzles.

E. G.  Delta Waves(1-4Hz) are slow brainwaves, Theta waves(4-8Hz) are particularly involved in day-dreaming and sleep, and Alpha waves (8-12Hz) dominate during moments of quiet thought, and similar meditative states,etc.
